         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in all [diseases] concerning wind [and] gall ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [the remedy] for a pain in the ... . Fagonia arabica ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... seed of (Holarrhena) antidysenterica, Berberis aristata, Piper longum, gin(ger) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... rice porridge, dhanya beans, Phaseolus radiatus, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the root of sacca, Withania somnifera, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [it is] to be drunk [and] to be ... in the nostrils ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the oil of (Sanseviera zeylanica), ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a9"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the viscous sediment [is] to be cooked ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (Helle)bor(us niger) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... as a remedy. Ginger, Plumbago zeylanica, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... a root (of) ... . ... of oleander ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... extract of divine sucker (?), extract of ants, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... as help (?) for the säṅkwi [disease], (the root) of oleander ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the oil of (sesam)e, cooked together ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... mashed [leaves] of Tribulus terrestris, two trau ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... for the two kinds of wounds, Hedyotis (umbellata) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b9"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... of ... </seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">This text is an older version than the Berlin one; this is in accordance with the use of the dual <hi>wi trauñc</hi> in this text vs. plural <hi>wi traunta</hi> in the younger parallel.</note><note type="parallels"><ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/></note><note type="philcomment">This fragment is a direct parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> a4ff., which was already stated by <bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1955a"/><citedRange>40</citedRange></bibl> but without further discussion.</note><note type="remarks">A fragment from the middle of a leaf. Recto and verso side can be determined due to the Berlin parallel. The Paris fragment <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkas9a"/> cannot belong to the same leaf, but it belongs to the same manuscript.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">There is no parallel in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/>, so any restoration remains unclear.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> a5.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> a6, but here the word <hi>sāṃtke</hi> is missing, which happens also otherwise in this text (b5). pw(ā)sane may be the loc.pl. of a word <hi>pu</hi> of unknown meaning.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> a7.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> a8.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> a9.</note><note corresp="#a7" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> a10. <hi>ṣikṣäll(e)</hi> is the gerund of a Prs VIII stem of an otherwise unattested root <hi>ṣik</hi>-.</note><note corresp="#a8" type="philcomment">The text in the Berlin parallel is lost.</note><note corresp="#a9" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> b2. This has the reading <hi>kālkä</hi>. It is in any case a loan word from Skt. <hi>kalka</hi>- 'viscous sediment deposited by oily substances when ground'.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> b4.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> b5.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Parallel to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> b7.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">One can read <hi>tsaukente</hi> or <hi>tsaukenne</hi>; in any case it helps to correct the uncertain reading of <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> b8 by Sieg/Siegling. This form can be locative plural or genitive singular. The next word is <hi>tsarātre</hi>, which has a second occurrence preceded by the epithet <hi>wärmiye</hi> 'pertaining to ant'. Therefore one may assume that <hi>ñäkciye tsaukente</hi> refers to another type of <hi>tsarātre</hi>. The whole phrase is maybe the calque of a Sanskrit word. As far as <hi>tsarātre</hi> is concerned, ants are known as a component of medicine, and <hi>tsarātre</hi> itself can be connected with <hi>tsär<hi rend="superscript">ā</hi></hi>- 'separate', hence 'extract', as per <bibl><title corresp="ref:adams2013a"/><citedRange>799</citedRange></bibl>. A connection of <hi>tsaukente</hi> with <hi>tsuk</hi>- 'to suck' is, of course, also likely, but <hi>tsauke</hi>* ‘drink’ as per <bibl><title corresp="ref:adams2013a"/><citedRange>813</citedRange></bibl>, i.e., 'divine drink' does not make much sense in this context. Rather, we have a nomen agentis 'sucker', referring to an insect such as louse, making a parallel with ant. Accordingly, a gen.sg. of <hi>tsauke<hi rend="subscript">u</hi></hi>* 'lit. sucker' is more likely.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">The parallel text <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> b9 has a slightly different wording <hi>s(·)ānto saṅkī(ts sā)ṃ(tk)e</hi> ||. The form <hi>säṅwits</hi> is a gen.pl. for <hi>säṅkwiṃts</hi>; the cluster ‹ṅw› ought to be the older spelling of younger <hi>saṅki</hi>- in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-w40"/> a3. The acc.pl. <hi>sänkiṃ</hi> occurs in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-w40"/> a3 in a list of diseases: <hi>pikṣanma säṅkiṃ yoraiṃ</hi> which are cured by anointing, so that it probably refers to a skin disease.</note><note corresp="#b9" type="philcomment"><hi>natsä</hi> should be the end of a gen.pl. form in -<hi>naṃts</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
