               <item n="m_philcomment_old">&lt;p&gt;This fragment is a direct parallel to [[THT 497]] a4ff., which was already stated by [[Couvreur 1955a]]: 40 but without further discussion.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a1.&lt;/b&gt; There is no parallel in [[THT 497]], so any restoration remains unclear.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a2.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] a5.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a3.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] a6, but here the word &lt;i&gt;sāṃtke&lt;/i&gt; is missing, which happens also otherwise in this text (b5). pw(ā)sane may be the loc.pl. of a word &lt;i&gt;pu&lt;/i&gt; of unknown meaning.&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a4.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] a7.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a5.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] a8.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a6.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] a9.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a7.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] a10. &lt;i&gt;ṣikṣäll(e)&lt;/i&gt; is the gerund of a Prs VIII stem of an otherwise unattested root &lt;i&gt;ṣik&lt;/i&gt;-.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a8.&lt;/b&gt; The text in the Berlin parallel is lost.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a9.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] b2. This has the reading &lt;i&gt;kālkä&lt;/i&gt;. It is in any case a loan word from Skt. &lt;i&gt;kalka&lt;/i&gt;- 'viscous sediment deposited by oily substances when ground'.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b1.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] b4.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b2.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] b5.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b3.&lt;/b&gt; Parallel to [[THT 497]] b7.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b4.&lt;/b&gt; One can read &lt;i&gt;tsaukente&lt;/i&gt; or &lt;i&gt;tsaukenne&lt;/i&gt;; in any case it helps to correct the uncertain reading of [[THT 497]] b8 by Sieg/Siegling. This form can be locative plural or genitive singular. The next word is &lt;i&gt;tsarātre&lt;/i&gt;, which has a second occurrence preceded by the epithet &lt;i&gt;wärmiye&lt;/i&gt; 'pertaining to ant'. Therefore one may assume that &lt;i&gt;ñäkciye tsaukente&lt;/i&gt; refers to another type of &lt;i&gt;tsarātre&lt;/i&gt;. The whole phrase is maybe the calque of a Sanskrit word. As far as &lt;i&gt;tsarātre&lt;/i&gt; is concerned, ants are known as a component of medicine, and &lt;i&gt;tsarātre&lt;/i&gt; itself can be connected with &lt;i&gt;tsär&lt;sup&gt;ā&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/i&gt;- 'separate', hence 'extract', as per [[Adams, 2DoT]]: 799. A connection of &lt;i&gt;tsaukente&lt;/i&gt; with &lt;i&gt;tsuk&lt;/i&gt;- 'to suck' is, of course, also likely, but &lt;i&gt;tsauke&lt;/i&gt;* ‘drink’ as per [[Adams, 2DoT]]: 813, i.e., 'divine drink' does not make much sense in this context. Rather, we have a nomen agentis 'sucker', referring to an insect such as louse, making a parallel with ant. Accordingly, a gen.sg. of &lt;i&gt;tsauke&lt;sub&gt;u&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/i&gt;* 'lit. sucker' is more likely.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b5.&lt;/b&gt; The parallel text [[THT 497]] b9 has a slightly different wording &lt;i&gt;s(·)ānto saṅkī(ts sā)ṃ(tk)e&lt;/i&gt; ||. The form &lt;i&gt;säṅwits&lt;/i&gt; is a gen.pl. for &lt;i&gt;säṅkwiṃts&lt;/i&gt;; the cluster ‹ṅw› ought to be the older spelling of younger &lt;i&gt;saṅki&lt;/i&gt;- in [[THT 497]] and [[W 40]] a3. The acc.pl. &lt;i&gt;sänkiṃ&lt;/i&gt; occurs in [[W 40]] a3 in a list of diseases: &lt;i&gt;pikṣanma säṅkiṃ yoraiṃ&lt;/i&gt; which are cured by anointing, so that it probably refers to a skin disease.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b9.&lt;/b&gt; &lt;i&gt;natsä&lt;/i&gt; should be the end of a gen.pl. form in -&lt;i&gt;naṃts&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</item>
